Identify and describe the boundaries of the abdomino-pelvic cavity 

Anterior: 

-External obliques 

-Internal obliques 

-Transverse obliques (innermost) 

 

Posterior: 

-Psoas major for vertical rotation: left/right and forward/backward 

-Psoas minor for upward pelvic rotation 

 

Superior:  

-Diaphragm, and structures passing through eg vena cava, aorta, esophagus, note attachment of psoas major to vertebral column 

 

Inferior: 

-Pelvic floor: levator ani, coccygeus 

 

Revise the orientation of abdominal muscle fibers 

 

 

Note distinction from intercostal muscle: external/internal are similarly oriented, but innermost intercostal is vertical as opposed to horizontal. 

 

Describe the division of the abdomen into 9 regions. What organs are in each? 

Vertical: midclavicular 

Horizontal: L1 and L5 lines 

Epigastric: Liver, Stomach, Pancreas 

LH: Stomach, spleen, left kidney (mainly LH) 

RH: Liver, gallbladder, right kidney 

Umbilical: transverse colon, small intestines, stomach, pancreas 

LL: Descending colon, small intestines, small portion of kidney 

RL: Ascending colon, small intestines, small portion of kidney 

Hypogastric: Small intestines, bladder, sigmoid colon, rectum, uterus,  

LI: Sigmoid colon, descending colon, small intestines 

RI: Caecum, ascending colon, small intestines, appendix 

 

 

Describe the division of the abdomen into quadrants 

Vertical: medial plane 

Horizontal: trans-umbilical plane

Embryonic development 

Foregut produces stomach and start of the duodenum. The foregut has both a dorsal and ventral mesogastrium. The liver develops in the ventral mesogastrium. The spleen develops in the dorsal mesogastrium.  

 

The midgut produces most of the duodenum, the jejunum, the ileum, and the proximal (cecum, ascending, transverse) colon. The hindgut produces the rest of the colon and rectum. 

 

The foregut, midgut and hindgut are supplied by the celiac trunk, superior mesenteric and inferior mesenteric arteries respectively. 

 

Enteric nervous system 

 

 

Note: Schabadasch's plexus = external, Meissner's plexus = internal 

 

All autonomic (parasympathetic and sympathetic) and somatic sensory nerves are connected to the myenteric plexus, which is then connected to the circular + longitudinal muscle and submucosal plexus. The submucosal plexus is connected to secretory cells, endocrine cells, blood vessels, and mechano- + chemoreceptors, and muscularis mucosae.  

 

Note: sympathetic innervation of abdomino-pelvic structures occur via the celiac ganglion, superior mesenteric ganglion, and inferior mesenteric ganglion.  

 

Blood supply 

Celiac trunk occurs at T12-L1. This branches off into the common hepatic, splenic, and left gastric arteries. Splenic artery branches off to give dorsal pancreatic artery. Below the celiac trunk, the superior mesenteric artery branches off the abdominal artery. Then comes the pair of renal arteries, followed by the inferior mesenteric artery.
